<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec-5-4" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Laplace Transforms of Periodic Functions</title>

    <p>
      In  <xref ref="sec-5-1" />, we computed the Laplace transforms of the periodic functions <m>\sin(\omega t)</m> and <m>\cos(\omega t)</m> that are continuous.
      In applications, we also have to address periodic functions that are periodic but piecewise continuous on <m>[0, \infty).</m> A function <m>f</m> is said to be <em>periodic</em> on <m>(-\infty, \infty)</m> if there exists a number <m>T&gt;0,</m> called a <em>period</em> of <m>f,</m> such that
      <me>
        f(t) = f(t+T)\quad\text{ for all } t\in (-\infty, \infty).
      </me>
      Graphically, a periodic function <m>f</m> repeats the portion of its graph restricted to <m>[0, T]</m> across subsequent intervals of the same length <m>T</m>.
    </p>

    <p>
      A piecewise continuous periodic function <m>f(t)</m> with a period <m>T</m> has the following property:
      <me>
        f(t) = f(t+T)  = f(t+2T) = \cdots = f(t+nT)
      </me>
      for all positive integers <m>n.</m> This property is visualized in 
      <xref ref="fig-piecewise-periodic-1" /> below.

      <figure xml:id="fig-piecewise-periodic-1">
        <caption>The graph of <m>f(t)</m>.</caption>
        <image>
          <latex-image>
   	    \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=1]
		\begin{axis}[
			axis lines=middle,
			xmin=-3.2, xmax=3.2,
			ymin=-1.1, ymax=1.5,
			xtick={-3, -2,-1,0,1,2,3},
			ytick={-1,0,1},
			xlabel={$t$},
			ylabel={$f(t)$},
			grid=both,
			width=13cm,
			height=5cm,
			samples=200,
			domain=0:6,
			]
			% Semicircular arcs: f(x) = sqrt(1 - (x - shift)^2)
			\addplot[blue, thick, domain=-3:-2]   {-0.5};
			\addplot[blue, thick, domain=-2:-1]   {sqrt(1 - (x +1)^2)};
			\addplot[blue, thick, domain=-1:0]   {-0.5};
			\addplot[blue, thick, domain=0:1]   {sqrt(1 - (x - 1)^2)};
			\addplot[blue, thick, domain=1:2]   {-0.5};
			\addplot[blue, thick, domain=2:3]   {sqrt(1 - (x - 3)^2)};
			%\node at (axis cs:1,1.1) {$f(x)$};
			% Dots to indicate discontinuities
			\foreach \x in {-2,0,2,4}
			\addplot[only marks, mark=*, blue] coordinates {(\x,0)};
			\foreach \x in {-2,0,2,4}
			\addplot[only marks, mark=*, fill=white, draw=blue]  coordinates {(\x,-0.5)};
				\foreach \x in {-3,-1,1,3}
			\addplot[only marks, mark=*, blue] coordinates {(\x,-0.5)};
			\foreach \x in {-1,1,3}
			\addplot[only marks, mark=*, fill=white, draw=blue]  coordinates {(\x,1)};
		\end{axis}
	    \end{tikzpicture}
          </latex-image>
        </image>
      </figure>
      To compute <m>\\mathcal{L}\{f(t)\},</m> we express it as an infinite series of integrals as follows:
      <me>
        \begin{split} \\mathcal{L}\{f(t)\}&amp; =\int_0^\infty f(t) e^{-st}\, dt\\ &amp;= \int_0^T f(t) e^{-st}\, dt+ \int_T^{2T} f(t) e^{-st}\, dt+ \int_{2T}^{3T} f(t) e^{-st}\, dt +\dots\\ &amp;=\int_0^T f(t) e^{-st}\, dt + \int_0^T f(t+T) e^{-s(t+T)}\, dt\\ &amp; \quad + \int_0^T f(t+2T) e^{-s(t+2T)}\, dt+ \dots+ \int_0^T f(t+nT) e^{-s(t+nT)}\, dt+\cdots\\ &amp;=\int_0^T f(t) e^{-st}\, dt\;\Big(1+e^{-sT}+ e^{-2sT} + \dots+ e^{-nsT}+\cdots \Big)\\ &amp;=\int_0^T f(t) e^{-st}\, dt\;\; \sum_{n=0}^\infty e^{-nsT}.
        \end{split}
      </me>
      Since the geometric series <m>\displaystyle \sum_{n=0}^\infty e^{-nsT}</m> converges for <m>s&gt;0</m> to <m>\displaystyle \frac{1}{1- e^{-sT}},</m> we obtain
      <men xml:id="Laplace-periodic-function">
        \boxed{\\mathcal{L}\{f(t)\} = \frac{1}{1- e^{-sT}}\int_0^T f(t) e^{-st}\, dt.}
      </men>
    </p>
  
  <example>
    <p>
      Let us revisit <m>\\mathcal{L}\{\sin(\omega t)\}.</m> 
    </p>
     </example> 
     <p>
      Using <xref ref="Laplace-periodic-function" /> with <m>T= 2\pi/\omega</m>, we obtain
      <me>
        \\mathcal{L}\{\sin(\omega t)\} = \frac{1}{1- e^{-2\pi s/\omega}}\int_0^{2\pi/\omega} \sin(\omega t) e^{-st}\, dt.
      </me>
      We compute
      <me>
        \int_0^{2\pi/\omega} \sin(\omega t) e^{-st}\, dt=\frac{\omega}{s^2+\omega^2}\left( 1- e^{-2\pi s/\omega}\right).
      </me>
      Hence
      <me>
        \\mathcal{L}\{\sin(\omega t)\} =\frac{\omega}{s^2+\omega^2},
      </me>
      as expected.
    </p>
  

  <p>
    The example above suggests that the direct computation of the Laplace transform of a periodic function may be more convenient.
  </p>

  <p>
    The example below concerns a periodic function acting as the source term of an initial value problem.
  </p>

  <example>
    <p>
      Consider the initial value problem <m>y'+ y = f(t), \; y(0) = 0,</m> where <m>f(t)</m> is given by
      <me>
        f(t) = \begin{cases} 1 &amp;\text{if } 0\le  t\le 1,\\ 0 &amp;\text{if } 1&lt; t &lt; 2, \end{cases}
      </me>
      and <m>f(t) = f(t+2)</m> for all <m>t</m> in <m>(-\infty, \infty).</m> 
    </p>
    </example>
    <p>
      The graph of <m>f</m> on <m>[0, \infty)</m> is shown below.
      <figure xml:id="fig-piecewise-periodic-2">
        <caption>The graph of <m>f(t)</m>.</caption>
        <image>
          <latex-image>
            \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=1]
	 			\begin{axis}[
	 					axis lines=middle,
	 					xmin=0, xmax=6.2,
	 					ymin=-0.2, ymax=1.5,
	 					xtick={0,1,2,3,4,5,6},
	 					ytick={0,1},
	 					xlabel={$t$},
	 					ylabel={$f(t)$},
	 					grid=both,
	 					width=13cm,
	 					height=5cm,
	 					samples=100,
	 					domain=0:6,
	 					]
	 					% Square wave segments (period 2: [0,1)=1, [1,2)=-1, repeat)
	 					\addplot[blue, thick, domain=0:1]   {1};
	 					\addplot[blue, thick, domain=1:2]   {0};
	 					\addplot[blue, thick, domain=2:3]   {1};
	 					\addplot[blue, thick, domain=3:4]   {0};
	 					\addplot[blue, thick, domain=4:5]   {1};
	 					\addplot[blue, thick, domain=5:6]   {0};
	 					\addplot[blue, thick, domain=6:6.1] {1};
		 					% Dots to indicate discontinuities
	 					\foreach \x in {0,1,2,3,4,5,6}
	 					\addplot[only marks, mark=*, blue] coordinates {(\x,1)};
	 					\foreach \x in {1,2,3,4, 5,6}
	 					\addplot[only marks, mark=*, fill=white, draw=blue] coordinates {(\x,0)};
	 				\end{axis}
	 		\end{tikzpicture}
          </latex-image>
        </image>
      </figure>
    </p>
  <p>
    Then
    <me>
      \begin{split} F(s) &amp;= \frac{1}{1-e^{-2s}}\int_0^2 f(t) e^{-st}\, dt\\ &amp;= \frac{1}{1-e^{-2s}}\int_0^1 e^{-st}\, dt\\ &amp;  = \frac{1}{1-e^{-2s}}\left(\frac{e^{-s}-1}{-s}\right)\\ &amp;= \frac{1}{s(1+e^{-s})}.
      \end{split}
    </me>
    Taking the Laplace transform of the differential equation, we get
    <me>
      sY(s) - y(0) + Y(s) = F(s).
    </me>
    With <m>y(0) = 0,</m> we have
    <me>
      Y(s) = \frac{1}{s(s+1)(1+e^{-s})}.
    </me>
    Since
    <me>
      \displaystyle \frac{1}{s(s+1)} = \frac{1}{s}- \frac{1}{s+1}
    </me>
    and
    <me>
      \displaystyle\frac{1}{1+e^{-s}} = \sum_{n=0}^\infty (-1)^ne^{-ns},
    </me>
    it follows that
    <me>
      Y(s) = \left(\frac{1}{s}- \frac{1}{s+1}\right)\sum_{n=0}^\infty (-1)^ne^{-ns}.
    </me>
    In view of the shifting on the <m>t-</m>axis property discussed in 
     <xref ref="shifting-on-t-axis" />, the solution <m>y(t)</m> of the initial value problem is
    <me>
      y(t)  =  \sum_{n=0}^{\infty}(-1)^n \\mathcal{U}(t-n)\; (1- e^{-(t-n)}).
    </me>
    The graph of this solution is in <xref ref="fig-piecewise-periodic-3" /> below. 
    The solution <m>y(t)</m> is a piecewise continuous periodic function with period 2,
     and it converges to the periodic function <m>f(t)</m> as <m>t\to\infty.</m>
    
